            It is certainly the ambition
of the biologically oriented majority of <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">psychiatrists</ENAMEX> to produce a manual of
mental <ENAMEX TYPE="DISEASE">disorders</ENAMEX> which, as the saying goes, "carves nature at its <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">joints</ENAMEX>"--one
which lists diseases that are each traceable to a unique, identifiable
malfunction in the brain. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DSM</ENAMEX> as it now stands, however, has no
pretensions to being such a manual. The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DSM</ENAMEX> is neutral as regards
etiology, which is to say that its disorders are grouped according to
observable symptoms rather than presumed cause. If you look up a disorder in
the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">DSM</ENAMEX> , you will find that it's defined by a list of problems (such as
impaired motor activity, or feeling numb and empty), a certain number of which
qualify a <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">person</ENAMEX> as having the disease.

